es within that package? Hmm, maybe not, since it’s tied to that named module. I’m curious about the ClassLoader and its ability to define a new class within the same package’s module. It seems like I’m running into a challenge with dynamic classes that aren't actually part of the module. Let’s think this through!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering decoding options**\\n\\nI’m thinking about using MimeDecoder or possibly simple string concatenation. It seems like I need to check the package path to see which might be the best approach. There’s a lot to consider when deciding on the appropriate method for decoding. I want to make sure I’m choosing the most efficient and effective option, so I’ll delve into the details and get that sorted out!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_OctbfNw7aKyTlnHQsLpEsfc4|fc_060b9a2a5f3480d0016a2aedb54b5c81968e834f275a69fa24", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.mockito/mockito-core/5.0.0/src/test/java/org_mockito/mockito_core/ModuleHandlerInnerModuleSystemFoundTest.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_mockito.mockito_core;\n\nimport org.graalvm.internal.tck.NativeImageSupport;\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;\nimport org.mockito.MockMakers;\nimport org.mockito.Mockito;\n\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.lang.module.Configuration;\nimport java.lang.module.ModuleFinder;\nimport java.nio.file.Files;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.util.Base64;\nimport java.util.Set;\n\nimport static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;\n\npublic class ModuleHandlerInnerModuleSystemFoundTest {\n    private static final String MODULE_NAME = \"mockito.fixture\";\n    private static final String HIDDEN_TYPE_NAME = \"fixture.hidden.HiddenType\";\n    private static final String MODULE_INFO_CLA